GoHighLevel (GHL) provides an official HTTP-based Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that enables AI agents to read and write GHL data—such as calendars, contacts, and opportunities—without custom SDKs [1]. It uses Private Integration Tokens (PITs) for secure, permission-based access [1].

Because some clients like Claude Desktop require stdio-based transport, several open-source community MCP servers exist to bridge this gap [2][3][4]. These allow you to integrate GHL via `npx` or local configuration [2]. Example configuration for a community server in Claude Desktop:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "ghl-mcp": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "ghl-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "GHL_API_KEY": "pit-your-token-here",
        "GHL_LOCATION_ID": "your-location-id"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

These community implementations offer varying levels of tool coverage, from basic API endpoints to curated "agency-grade" workflows and multi-tenant support [2][3][5].
